    "content": "<html lang=\"en\">\n<head>\n<meta charset=\"UTF-8\" />\n<meta name=\"viewport\" content=\"width=device-width, initial-scale=1\" />\n<title>Type System Demonstration</title>\n<style>\n  body {\n    font-family: Arial, sans-serif;\n    margin: 2rem;\n    background-color: #f9fafb;\n    color: #333;\n  }\n  h1 {\n    text-align: center;\n  }\n  section {\n    max-width: 700px;\n    margin: 2rem auto;\n    background: white;\n    padding: 1.5rem 2rem;\n    border-radius: 8px;\n    box-shadow: 0 2px 8px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);\n  }\n  pre {\n    background: #eee;\n    padding: 1rem;\n    overflow-x: auto;\n    border-radius: 6px;\n  }\n  button {\n    background-color: #0078d7;\n    color: white;\n    border: none;\n    padding: 0.5rem 1rem;\n    border-radius: 5px;\n    cursor: pointer;\n    font-weight: bold;\n    margin-top: 1rem;\n  }\n  button:hover {\n    background-color: #005ea1;\n  }\n  .output {\n    background: #272822;\n    color: #f8f8f2;\n    padding: 1rem;\n    border-radius: 6px;\n    margin-top: 1rem;\n    font-family: \"Courier New\", Courier, monospace;\n    white-space: pre-wrap;\n  }\n  .label {\n    font-weight: bold;\n    margin-top: 1.5rem;\n  }\n</style>\n</head>\n<body>\n<h1>Understanding Type Systems in Programming</h1>\n<section>\n  <p>A <em>type system</em> is a set of rules that assigns a property called <strong>type</strong> to various constructs - such as variables, expressions, functions or modules - in a computer program. It helps detect errors, enforce constraints, and improve program reliability.</p>\n  \n  <h2>Key Concepts</h2>\n  <ul>\n    <li><strong>Type Safety:</strong> Guarantees that operations only get applied to compatible data types.</li>\n    <li><strong>Static Typing:</strong> Types are checked at compile time (e.g., Java, C#).</li>\n    <li><strong>Dynamic Typing:</strong> Types are checked at runtime (e.g., JavaScript, Python).</li>\n    <li><strong>Strong vs Weak Typing:</strong> Determines how strictly types are enforced or coerced.</li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <h2>Example: JavaScript's Dynamic & Weak Type System</h2>\n  <p>JavaScript is dynamically typed and weakly typed, meaning variables can hold values of any type and implicit type coercion can occur.</p>\n  \n  <pre><code>\n// Variable can hold any type\nlet value = 42;       // number\nvalue = \"hello\";      // now a string\n\n// Implicit coercion in addition\nconsole.log(2 + \"3\"); // \"23\" (number + string => string concatenation)\n\n// Comparison quirks\nconsole.log(0 == false);   // true (weak equality)\nconsole.log(0 === false);  // false (strict equality)\n  </code></pre>\n  <button id=\"run-js-demo\">Run Demo Code</button>\n  <div class=\"output\" id=\"js-output\"></div>\n\n  <h2>Example: A Simple Static Type System Check</h2>\n  <p>Let's simulate a very simple static type checker for a small expression language:</p>\n  \n  <pre><code>\n// Expressions can be numbers or booleans\n// Addition only allowed with numbers\n\nfunction typeCheck(expr) {\n  if (typeof expr === \"number\") return \"number\";\n  if (typeof expr === \"boolean\") return \"boolean\";\n  if (expr.op === \"+\") {\n    const leftType = typeCheck(expr.left);\n    const rightType = typeCheck(expr.right);\n    if (leftType === \"number\" && rightType === \"number\") return \"number\";\n    throw new Error(\"TypeError: '+' requires number + number\");\n  }\n  throw new Error(\"TypeError: Unknown expression\");\n}\n\n// Example:\nconst expr = { op: \"+\", left: 5, right: { op: \"+\", left: 3, right: 10 } };\n// const invalid = { op: \"+\", left: true, right: 1 };\n  </code></pre>\n\n  <button id=\"run-typecheck-demo\">Run Type Checker Demo</button>\n  <div class=\"output\" id=\"tc-output\"></div>\n</section>\n\n<script>\n  const jsOutput = document.getElementById(\"js-output\");\n  document.getElementById(\"run-js-demo\").addEventListener(\"click\", () => {\n    jsOutput.textContent = \"\"; // clear\n    function log(...args) {\n      jsOutput.textContent += args.map(a => typeof a === \"string\" ? a : JSON.stringify(a)).join(\" \") + \"\\n\";\n    }\n\n    try {\n      let value = 42;\n      log(\"Initial value:\", value, \"(type:\", typeof value + \")\");\n      value = \"hello\";\n      log(\"After reassignment:\", value, \"(type:\", typeof value + \")\");\n      log('2 + \"3\" =', 2 + \"3\");\n      log('0 == false:', 0 == false);\n      log('0 === false:', 0 === false);\n    } catch(e) {\n      jsOutput.textContent += \"Error: \" + e.message;\n    }\n  });\n\n  const tcOutput = document.getElementById(\"tc-output\");\n  document.getElementById(\"run-typecheck-demo\").addEventListener(\"click\", () => {\n    tcOutput.textContent = \"\"; // clear\n\n    function typeCheck(expr) {\n      if (typeof expr === \"number\") return \"number\";\n      if (typeof expr === \"boolean\") return \"boolean\";\n      if (typeof expr === \"object\" && expr !== null) {\n        if (expr.op === \"+\") {\n          const leftType = typeCheck(expr.left);\n          const rightType = typeCheck(expr.right);\n          if (leftType === \"number\" && rightType === \"number\") return \"number\";\n          throw new Error(\"TypeError: '+' requires number + number, got \" + leftType + \" + \" + rightType);\n        }\n      }\n      throw new Error(\"TypeError: Unknown expression\");\n    }\n\n    const expr = { op: \"+\", left: 5, right: { op: \"+\", left: 3, right: 10 } };\n    const invalid = { op: \"+\", left: true, right: 1 };\n\n    try {\n      let t1 = typeCheck(expr);\n      tcOutput.textContent += \"Expression type: \" + t1 + \"\\n\";\n      tcOutput.textContent += \"Evaluation result: \" + (evaluate(expr)) + \"\\n\\n\";\n    } catch(e) {\n      tcOutput.textContent += e.message + \"\\n\\n\";\n    }\n\n    try {\n      let t2 = typeCheck(invalid);\n      tcOutput.textContent += \"Invalid expr type: \" + t2 + \"\\n\";\n      tcOutput.textContent += \"Evaluation result: \" + (evaluate(invalid)) + \"\\n\";\n    } catch(e) {\n      tcOutput.textContent += e.message + \"\\n\";\n    }\n\n    // Simple evaluator for the expression\n    function evaluate(expr) {\n      if (typeof expr === \"number\") return expr;\n      if (typeof expr === \"boolean\") return expr;\n      if (expr.op === \"+\") {\n        return evaluate(expr.left) + evaluate(expr.right);\n      }\n      throw new Error(\"Unknown expression\");\n    }\n  });\n</script>\n</body>\n</html>"
